WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:04.600
I am so excited to be here.

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:07.240
This is my fourth year at the POSIT Conference,

00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:10.240
and I've been looking forward to this event for months.

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:15.440
For me, one of the most magical places on earth

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:16.780
is POSIT Conf.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:19.959
Just like at Disney World,

00:00:19.959 --> 00:00:22.540
I get to meet my favorite celebrities,

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:26.920
take home awesome souvenirs,

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:29.959
and take photos in front of iconic landmarks.

00:00:31.799 --> 00:00:32.840
And even though we can't be

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:35.720
in this magical place every day,

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:39.119
what we can do is create a community back at home

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:41.279
that feels just as magical.

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:45.480
My name is Melissa Van Bussel.

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:48.840
I'm a senior analyst at Statistics Canada,

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:53.099
and I help run a large polyglot data science community

00:00:53.099 --> 00:00:56.980
at my workplace called the R and Python User Group.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:00.860
Our group is pretty magical,

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:02.660
and today I want to share with you

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:05.339
some of the things that make it so magical,

00:01:05.339 --> 00:01:07.220
and I also want to share how you can create

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:09.559
your own magical polyglot community.

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:15.220
The R and Python User Group at Statistics Canada

00:01:15.220 --> 00:01:17.900
has over 1,000 members,

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:20.300
all of whom have different levels of experience

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:21.540
with programming,

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:24.160
and who all use different programming languages.

00:01:25.879 --> 00:01:28.900
In our group, we really hold the philosophy

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:32.599
that the community aspect is far more important

00:01:32.599 --> 00:01:35.000
than the programming language that someone uses.

00:01:36.339 --> 00:01:39.900
In the same way that Disney World isn't about Mickey Mouse,

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:42.540
your data science community doesn't have to be

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:44.440
about one specific language.

00:01:46.599 --> 00:01:49.419
And in fact, part of what makes going to Disney World

00:01:49.419 --> 00:01:52.379
so magical is the fact that you can see

00:01:52.379 --> 00:01:55.519
all of your favorite characters all in one place.

00:01:57.300 --> 00:01:58.739
That's why the name of our group

00:01:58.739 --> 00:02:02.139
has both R and Python in it,

00:02:02.139 --> 00:02:04.900
so that our members don't feel like they have to choose

00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:06.400
between one or the other.

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:10.220
Don't be too misled by this name, though,

00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:12.639
because even though it's only got two languages

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:16.619
in the title, we do tend to be the go-to

00:02:16.619 --> 00:02:20.380
for all things technical at our workplace.

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:24.059
It's just that the acronym RPUG is a lot nicer to say

00:02:24.059 --> 00:02:26.119
than whatever this one would be.

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:31.779
By creating a group that embraces

00:02:31.779 --> 00:02:34.300
multiple programming languages,

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:37.779
you're ensuring that your group is going to stay relevant,

00:02:37.779 --> 00:02:40.360
regardless of which language or tool

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:42.860
ends up becoming the most popular over time.

00:02:43.179 --> 00:02:46.419
And if you want to create your own Polyglot community,

00:02:46.419 --> 00:02:49.220
it turns out that you don't need a magic wand to do it.

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:52.179
I'm going to share a few of the strategies

00:02:52.179 --> 00:02:55.419
that have been working well for us at Statistics Canada,

00:02:55.419 --> 00:02:57.460
and hopefully that'll help spark some ideas

00:02:57.460 --> 00:02:58.899
for your own group as well.

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:05.339
If you ask somebody to introduce themselves,

00:03:05.339 --> 00:03:07.539
especially at this conference,

00:03:07.539 --> 00:03:09.580
you'll notice that people's introductions

00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:11.500
you'll notice that people's introductions

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:15.460
usually include the programming language that they use.

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:18.339
Someone might describe themselves as an R person

00:03:18.339 --> 00:03:21.479
or as a Python person in the same sentence

00:03:21.479 --> 00:03:24.820
where they tell you what their name is and where they work.

00:03:26.199 --> 00:03:29.360
For a lot of us, the programming language that we use

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:32.160
can feel very core to our identity.

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:38.059
And so if you want to create a successful Polyglot group,

00:03:38.059 --> 00:03:40.059
then my recommendation to you

00:03:40.059 --> 00:03:42.699
is to create branding for your group

00:03:42.699 --> 00:03:45.380
that people can identify with

00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:47.419
and can associate with your group.

00:03:47.419 --> 00:03:49.800
But more specifically, you want to make sure

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:54.100
that that branding isn't overly specific to one language.

00:03:55.940 --> 00:03:58.240
For the R and Python user group,

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:01.720
our branding is centered around our group's acronym,

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:03.779
which is RPUG.

00:04:03.779 --> 00:04:08.339
And in 2021, one of our members, Thomas Wood,

00:04:08.339 --> 00:04:12.380
created a logo for the group, which is a pirate pug.

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:18.660
This logo was created entirely using code,

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:21.140
which means it's completely reproducible

00:04:21.140 --> 00:04:23.820
and also pretty easy to modify,

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:25.519
which means that it wasn't long

00:04:25.519 --> 00:04:27.540
before other members of the group,

00:04:29.260 --> 00:04:31.839
other members of the group started creating spin-offs

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:33.660
of the original logo.

00:04:34.779 --> 00:04:37.380
As of today, we've got over 30 different versions

00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:40.380
of this logo, the stickers of which you can find

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:43.920
all over the place at the StatCan office in Ottawa.

00:04:45.859 --> 00:04:48.820
One of our other members, Alex McSween,

00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:51.299
who's actually here at Conf,

00:04:51.299 --> 00:04:54.859
created a 2025 RPUG calendar

00:04:54.859 --> 00:04:58.619
where each month of the year features a different pug

00:04:58.619 --> 00:05:00.260
based on that month's theme.

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:02.619
Over the last year, we've also hosted

00:05:02.619 --> 00:05:05.059
a couple of merch orders that have been centered

00:05:05.059 --> 00:05:06.299
around these logos.

00:05:08.859 --> 00:05:13.140
A brand isn't just a brand, and a logo isn't just a logo.

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:17.380
It's something that helps your members feel more connected

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:20.940
to something bigger than just the language that they use,

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:24.140
but more importantly, it also helps them feel connected

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:25.220
to your group.

00:05:25.339 --> 00:05:27.700
Once your group has its own identity,

00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:29.420
the next step is to make sure

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:31.500
that there's something for everyone.

00:05:32.579 --> 00:05:35.299
Because a polyglot group is going to have

00:05:35.299 --> 00:05:39.579
a wide variety of people, sort of by definition,

00:05:39.579 --> 00:05:42.940
you wanna create a multi-park experience

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:44.540
where every person in the group

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:47.140
feels like there's something that's for them.

00:05:50.019 --> 00:05:53.619
At Disney, we've also created a multi-park experience

00:05:54.380 --> 00:05:56.260
at Disney World.

00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:59.140
Epcot is the theme park that's the most focused

00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:01.660
on learning and exploration.

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:05.940
And in RPUG, we've got our own little version of Epcot

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:08.339
that provides our members with a number of ways

00:06:08.339 --> 00:06:11.179
that they can learn new skills related to open source.

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:15.500
For example, we have a monthly meeting

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:17.779
where we share updates about what's new

00:06:17.779 --> 00:06:22.140
in the world of open source and at Statistics Canada,

00:06:22.140 --> 00:06:26.100
followed by a presentation or a workshop

00:06:26.100 --> 00:06:27.220
from a guest speaker.

00:06:28.779 --> 00:06:30.859
We try to make sure that these presentations

00:06:30.859 --> 00:06:33.959
aren't super specific to one language

00:06:33.959 --> 00:06:36.940
by choosing topics that are broadly applicable

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:38.959
to anybody who works with data.

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:43.260
Over the last year, some of the topics that we've had

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:46.779
have included a showcase of internally developed

00:06:46.779 --> 00:06:51.260
R and Python packages, a roundup of success stories

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:53.540
when working with the parquet file format,

00:06:54.459 --> 00:06:57.700
and a presentation from the Statistics Canada library

00:06:57.700 --> 00:07:01.220
showing our members how they can access library resources

00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:03.299
to learn about open source topics.

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:08.399
We've also got an internal website that has guides

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:11.859
and tutorials for working with R and Python

00:07:11.859 --> 00:07:14.779
in a way that's specific to our workplace's

00:07:14.779 --> 00:07:16.140
technical infrastructure.

00:07:17.299 --> 00:07:20.820
And we've got a webpage that outlines project templates

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:22.619
and packages that have been developed

00:07:22.619 --> 00:07:24.720
by the members of our community.

00:07:27.519 --> 00:07:29.739
Hollywood Studios is the theme park

00:07:29.739 --> 00:07:32.459
that's all about going behind the scenes

00:07:32.459 --> 00:07:35.079
and seeing the hidden work that goes into making

00:07:35.079 --> 00:07:37.859
the published product before it ever ends up

00:07:37.859 --> 00:07:38.839
on the big screen.

00:07:40.260 --> 00:07:43.459
For us, that means giving people a safe space

00:07:43.459 --> 00:07:46.619
to try things out, to make mistakes,

00:07:46.619 --> 00:07:48.540
to learn, and to ask questions.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:53.739
We host low-stakes code challenges

00:07:53.739 --> 00:07:55.980
where the prompt can either be solved

00:07:55.980 --> 00:07:59.359
in just a couple of lines of code or in a lot more,

00:07:59.359 --> 00:08:01.500
depending on how creative the person wants to be

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:02.540
with their solution.

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:06.019
And participants are encouraged to have fun

00:08:06.019 --> 00:08:09.019
and be silly with it so that it doesn't feel like work.

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:13.959
You can use any language that you want for these challenges

00:08:13.959 --> 00:08:16.299
and this tends to be a space where people will

00:08:16.299 --> 00:08:19.239
often use a language that they're less comfortable in.

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:24.059
We've also got a number of different ways

00:08:24.059 --> 00:08:26.519
that our members can ask for help with programming

00:08:26.519 --> 00:08:28.339
or other technical questions.

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:33.260
We've got a very large chat on Microsoft Teams

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:36.460
where people ask questions casually throughout the day,

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:40.479
but we also have nine volunteers that offer

00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:43.340
drop-in office hours on a regular basis.

00:08:45.359 --> 00:08:47.940
Because the group is polyglot,

00:08:47.940 --> 00:08:50.520
each office hour clearly outlines

00:08:51.219 --> 00:08:52.679
which topics the current volunteer

00:08:52.679 --> 00:08:54.679
can answer questions about.

00:08:54.679 --> 00:08:58.599
And it also points users to the full list of office hours

00:08:58.599 --> 00:09:01.359
if they need help figuring out who the right person is

00:09:01.359 --> 00:09:03.919
that they should reach out to for a specific topic.

00:09:06.159 --> 00:09:08.219
If you've ever been to Disney World,

00:09:08.219 --> 00:09:11.780
then your favorite theme park is probably Magic Kingdom,

00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:15.679
which is a place all about having fun just for fun's sake.

00:09:16.679 --> 00:09:21.679
Over the last year, RPUG has had quite a few events

00:09:21.919 --> 00:09:26.359
that have had absolutely nothing to do with programming

00:09:26.359 --> 00:09:28.159
and have really just been an opportunity

00:09:28.159 --> 00:09:30.719
for like-minded people to hang out together

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:33.260
and do something fun outside of work hours.

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:36.400
We've had a couple of trivia nights

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:40.520
and recently we had an event called Beads and Brews

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:43.599
where we got together for dinner after work

00:09:43.599 --> 00:09:45.960
and then people could make friendship bracelets

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:48.679
or key chains or whatever else they wanted to make.

00:09:51.359 --> 00:09:54.840
This year, we're also launching an RPUG yearbook

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:57.320
just for fun where we can put all of the pictures

00:09:57.320 --> 00:09:59.119
from this year's events.

00:09:59.119 --> 00:10:02.359
And we'll also have a section for RPUG awards

00:10:02.359 --> 00:10:05.599
so that we can recognize the contributions of our members.

00:10:08.419 --> 00:10:10.280
Now a lot of the stuff that I've just talked about

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:12.599
might seem kind of silly,

00:10:12.599 --> 00:10:15.880
especially in the context of a group that in theory

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:18.479
is supposed to be focused on data science,

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:22.559
but having these fun activities is actually really important

00:10:22.559 --> 00:10:24.760
for keeping members engaged with your group.

00:10:25.799 --> 00:10:28.059
And if your group is polyglot,

00:10:28.059 --> 00:10:30.080
then I'd argue that this kind of thing

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:31.840
is even more important

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:34.520
because it's these types of events and activities

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:38.280
that are going to give your members a chance to connect

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:40.900
and figure out what stuff they do have in common.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:45.140
It's a lot harder for somebody to make a new friend

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:47.340
during a programming workshop

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:49.219
than it is for them to make a new friend

00:10:49.219 --> 00:10:51.460
while they're doing something fun and casual.

00:10:52.419 --> 00:10:53.820
And the more that the members of your group

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:55.260
are friends with each other,

00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:56.840
the more they're going to want to participate

00:10:56.840 --> 00:10:59.260
in your group's activities as a result.

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:05.460
Another way that you can increase participation

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:07.979
in your group is by taking a page

00:11:07.979 --> 00:11:09.539
out of Disney World's book.

00:11:10.539 --> 00:11:12.739
When you go to Disney World,

00:11:12.739 --> 00:11:16.140
you don't just feel like you're watching a bunch of actors.

00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:18.179
You feel like you're a character

00:11:18.179 --> 00:11:20.539
that actually belongs in the story.

00:11:21.539 --> 00:11:23.539
And you want to create this same kind of feeling

00:11:23.539 --> 00:11:24.440
within your group.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:28.299
One of the easiest ways that you can do this

00:11:28.299 --> 00:11:30.859
is by letting every member of the group

00:11:30.859 --> 00:11:33.739
be as involved as they want to be

00:11:33.739 --> 00:11:36.580
with the organization and the planning of the group.

00:11:36.979 --> 00:11:39.020
And if your group is polyglot,

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:41.979
again, this is going to be even more important

00:11:41.979 --> 00:11:45.380
because nobody is an expert at everything.

00:11:45.380 --> 00:11:48.460
So you want to make sure you've got a wide range of voices

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:52.020
so that each member of the group feels represented

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:54.900
and welcome, regardless of which languages

00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:56.219
or tools they use.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:01.020
In RPUG, we have the philosophy

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:04.780
that anybody who wants to contribute can.

00:12:05.619 --> 00:12:07.380
There's a few different ways that we do this,

00:12:07.380 --> 00:12:10.979
and one of them is the RPUG Weekly Newsletter.

00:12:10.979 --> 00:12:13.059
And anybody at Statistics Canada

00:12:13.059 --> 00:12:16.820
can publish something in this newsletter.

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:18.780
You actually don't even have to be a part of the group

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:20.419
to submit an article to it.

00:12:21.859 --> 00:12:24.820
What we get as a result is a weekly,

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:28.580
community-curated collection of upcoming events,

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:30.580
programming tips, and so on.

00:12:31.020 --> 00:12:34.140
We also have an internal RPUG website,

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:36.859
which anyone can contribute to,

00:12:36.859 --> 00:12:41.099
can contribute to, by submitting a merge request on GitLab.

00:12:41.099 --> 00:12:45.020
And I took these numbers directly from the repository,

00:12:45.020 --> 00:12:47.460
and we can see that in the last four months alone,

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:52.460
we've had 33 contributors across almost 2,000 commits.

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:57.179
This group is graphically,

00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.380
this group is grassroots,

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:02.539
it's really by users and for users,

00:13:02.539 --> 00:13:05.580
which means that the people who are organizing the group

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:08.539
are also the same people who actually use the tools

00:13:08.539 --> 00:13:10.099
on a regular basis,

00:13:10.099 --> 00:13:12.940
rather than people from senior management, for example.

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:18.219
We try really hard to keep things casual.

00:13:18.219 --> 00:13:21.900
We try to avoid getting too bogged down with bureaucracy.

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:23.619
But with that being said,

00:13:23.619 --> 00:13:27.059
of course, there is still a lot of work to be done.

00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:30.140
So, what is RPUG?

00:13:30.140 --> 00:13:33.219
RPUG is a community-based RPUG project

00:13:33.219 --> 00:13:36.260
that provides some structure to the group.

00:13:37.179 --> 00:13:39.380
To be honest, it would be basically impossible

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:41.580
to have a group of 1,000 people

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:44.219
and not have some type of structure.

00:13:44.219 --> 00:13:45.859
It definitely takes a village

00:13:45.859 --> 00:13:48.140
to have a group this large run smoothly.

00:13:50.619 --> 00:13:54.619
We have around 1,300 members in total,

00:13:54.619 --> 00:13:56.539
we call the RPUG committee.

00:13:59.059 --> 00:14:01.820
The committee is open to anyone,

00:14:01.820 --> 00:14:03.460
and it's as simple as just asking

00:14:03.460 --> 00:14:05.140
to be a part of the committee,

00:14:05.140 --> 00:14:07.780
but it does tend to be the more advanced programmers

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:09.260
who join this subset.

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:13.340
Personally, I really love being part of this committee.

00:14:13.340 --> 00:14:15.179
We meet every two weeks,

00:14:15.179 --> 00:14:17.580
and in addition to planning some of the fun stuff

00:14:17.580 --> 00:14:19.500
that I've talked about earlier today,

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:21.219
this is also the group that discusses

00:14:21.219 --> 00:14:22.940
the more technical topics.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:25.419
In particular, we talk a lot about

00:14:25.419 --> 00:14:27.739
how open-source tools are being used

00:14:27.739 --> 00:14:29.780
and supported in our workplace.

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:35.299
We've found that this model where anybody can join

00:14:35.299 --> 00:14:38.619
and everyone can be as involved as they want to be

00:14:38.619 --> 00:14:40.140
has worked pretty well for us.

00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:44.219
If you're in this room right now,

00:14:44.219 --> 00:14:47.400
it's probably because you're somebody who cares deeply

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:50.340
about building and sustaining data communities.

00:14:51.179 --> 00:14:54.739
And if that's you, then there's probably a good chance

00:14:54.739 --> 00:14:57.460
that one of the following scenarios applies to you.

00:14:59.859 --> 00:15:03.140
Maybe you're already part of an amazing group

00:15:03.140 --> 00:15:03.979
that's thriving.

00:15:05.979 --> 00:15:07.820
Maybe you're just starting out,

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:09.059
and you're wondering how to get

00:15:09.059 --> 00:15:10.700
your new group off the ground.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:15.580
Or maybe you're in the third camp,

00:15:15.580 --> 00:15:17.140
and you're part of a group that might be

00:15:17.140 --> 00:15:19.219
struggling a bit to stay afloat.

00:15:20.340 --> 00:15:24.619
Maybe you're in a smaller city or a smaller workplace,

00:15:24.619 --> 00:15:27.659
and so the pool of potential people

00:15:27.659 --> 00:15:30.880
that could possibly participate in your group

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:32.340
is just a little bit smaller.

00:15:34.820 --> 00:15:38.039
If the second or third one applies to you,

00:15:38.039 --> 00:15:39.940
then I would really encourage you

00:15:39.940 --> 00:15:42.780
to give the polyglot approach a chance.

00:15:44.119 --> 00:15:47.780
By doing so, you're multiplying your potential members,

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:50.580
you're multiplying your potential impact,

00:15:50.580 --> 00:15:53.299
and you might also learn a new programming language

00:15:53.299 --> 00:15:54.140
along the way.

00:15:57.299 --> 00:16:02.140
At the end of the day, it shouldn't be about R versus Python.

00:16:02.140 --> 00:16:03.859
It should be about creating a space

00:16:03.859 --> 00:16:05.940
where everybody feels welcome

00:16:05.940 --> 00:16:08.000
and is excited to learn from each other.

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:13.119
So regardless of which of these scenarios applies to you,

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:16.299
I hope that my talk gave you some ideas

00:16:16.299 --> 00:16:18.619
about how you can create a community

00:16:18.619 --> 00:16:21.760
that feels like a Disney world of data science.

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:24.820
If you're interested in creating

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:26.400
your own polyglot community

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:28.500
and you wanna connect to chat about it,

00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:30.859
I'm happy to take questions in just a second,

00:16:30.859 --> 00:16:33.059
or you can find my information up there

00:16:33.059 --> 00:16:34.700
and we can chat later.

00:16:34.700 --> 00:16:36.380
And if you're somebody who likes to collect

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:38.260
hex stickers at conf,

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:40.679
and you want your very own RPUG sticker,

00:16:40.679 --> 00:16:43.299
come say hi afterwards and I can give you one.

00:16:43.299 --> 00:16:44.380
Thanks.

00:16:44.539 --> 00:16:45.359
Thank you.

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:46.200
Thank you.

00:16:49.979 --> 00:16:51.099
Thank you so much.

00:16:51.099 --> 00:16:53.520
We have lots of questions here.

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:56.140
Several of them are interested in

00:16:56.140 --> 00:16:59.419
how you got started with the RPUG group

00:16:59.419 --> 00:17:04.140
and the trajectory of asking people to join

00:17:04.140 --> 00:17:08.380
and how you gathered the first group of people

00:17:08.380 --> 00:17:10.180
in order to start the group.

00:17:10.180 --> 00:17:11.780
Yeah, great question.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:13.959
I'm probably not the best person to ask about that

00:17:13.959 --> 00:17:17.400
because the group started in 2017

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:20.839
when I, like I didn't work at Statistics Canada back then.

00:17:20.839 --> 00:17:24.800
So I wasn't there for the early days of the group.

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:28.599
I joined StatCan in 2021.

00:17:28.599 --> 00:17:32.680
So by that point, there were already a few hundred people

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:36.040
in the group, so yeah.

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:38.359
Okay, but if you were to generalize that

00:17:38.359 --> 00:17:41.319
and give some advice about someone starting a group

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:44.959
from scratch, would you be able to offer

00:17:44.959 --> 00:17:49.680
any things you've learned so far about polyglot groups

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:52.180
to help someone get one off the ground?

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:55.359
Yeah, good question.

00:17:59.199 --> 00:18:03.459
Yeah, so I think the biggest tip that I would have

00:18:03.459 --> 00:18:07.160
is kind of like the section of my talk

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:11.079
where I was talking about doing things that are fun.

00:18:11.839 --> 00:18:14.760
I think the mistake that a lot of groups make

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:19.760
is they only focus on the technical side of things.

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:23.280
So it kind of feels like this is just a thing

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:25.599
that somebody is doing because their career

00:18:25.599 --> 00:18:27.640
is related to data.

00:18:28.959 --> 00:18:33.400
But if you want people to feel truly connected,

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:36.819
then having the fun stuff as well,

00:18:37.680 --> 00:18:39.400
I think is really important.

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:42.800
And also just recognizing that not every person

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:45.780
is gonna want to participate in everything.

00:18:45.780 --> 00:18:47.319
So there's gonna be some people

00:18:47.319 --> 00:18:49.680
who they're only gonna want to do the stuff

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:52.619
that is productive in the traditional sense,

00:18:52.619 --> 00:18:55.280
like workshops or whatever else.

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:56.680
And then there's gonna be other people

00:18:56.680 --> 00:19:00.479
who only want to do the fun stuff, so.

00:19:01.739 --> 00:19:03.239
Really good advice, thank you.

00:19:04.719 --> 00:19:05.800
Very important question,

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:08.199
which is your favorite RPUG variant sticker?

00:19:08.880 --> 00:19:11.239
Ah, okay, that's a great question,

00:19:11.239 --> 00:19:13.520
and I have to be careful about my answer

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:15.040
because Alex has made a lot of them

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:17.420
and she's sitting in the third row here.

00:19:19.479 --> 00:19:22.000
But, okay, I'll try to go back to them.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:23.739
No, that's probably way too impossible.

00:19:23.739 --> 00:19:25.739
No, it's just not gonna load at all now.

00:19:27.979 --> 00:19:32.979
So my favorite one is probably like the reindeer,

00:19:32.979 --> 00:19:35.939
like Rudolph, it's called Rudolph the Red-Nosed Pug.

00:19:36.099 --> 00:19:39.540
And I think that might have been,

00:19:39.540 --> 00:19:40.819
was that the one that won,

00:19:40.819 --> 00:19:42.819
there was like a competition this year

00:19:42.819 --> 00:19:45.099
where people voted for their favorite ones

00:19:45.099 --> 00:19:47.739
and I think that one, was that the winner?

00:19:47.739 --> 00:19:48.560
Yeah.

00:19:51.219 --> 00:19:52.060
Perfect.

00:19:52.060 --> 00:19:55.739
Do you have trouble sharing demos between teammates

00:19:55.739 --> 00:19:57.219
for those teams with sensitive data

00:19:57.219 --> 00:19:59.500
that can't be shared with other teams?

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:00.719
Sorry, can you repeat the first part?

00:20:00.719 --> 00:20:02.619
Yeah, do you have trouble sharing demos

00:20:02.619 --> 00:20:06.459
or workflows with teammates that have sensitive data

00:20:06.459 --> 00:20:08.060
that can't be shared with other teams

00:20:08.060 --> 00:20:12.500
or is that not really an issue for our pug group?

00:20:12.500 --> 00:20:13.900
Yeah, good question.

00:20:15.619 --> 00:20:20.619
So almost all of our meetings are internal people only.

00:20:22.219 --> 00:20:27.219
So even if we can't share like the specific data

00:20:27.319 --> 00:20:29.260
that somebody's working on,

00:20:29.420 --> 00:20:33.819
they can probably share the code that's on GitLab.

00:20:33.819 --> 00:20:36.020
We can't put any data on there anyways,

00:20:36.020 --> 00:20:37.699
so everything that's on GitLab

00:20:37.699 --> 00:20:41.180
is already abstracted away from the code.

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:45.000
So I wouldn't say we have too much trouble with that.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:45.839
Great.

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:50.359
Is the group all in Ottawa or are some remote?

00:20:50.359 --> 00:20:53.339
And if the latter, how do you keep the remote people engaged

00:20:53.339 --> 00:20:55.180
particularly with fun events?

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:57.099
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:20:57.939 --> 00:21:00.859
No, not everybody is in Ottawa.

00:21:00.859 --> 00:21:04.060
We have like offices in a bunch of major cities

00:21:04.060 --> 00:21:05.900
across Canada.

00:21:05.900 --> 00:21:09.219
So we have some events that are in-person only

00:21:09.219 --> 00:21:12.459
like the trivia nights or the beads and brews,

00:21:12.459 --> 00:21:17.459
but then we have our monthly meetings as hybrid,

00:21:18.060 --> 00:21:21.300
but we also have some events that are virtual only.

00:21:21.300 --> 00:21:26.300
So we have like our pug virtual coffee hour

00:21:27.939 --> 00:21:29.739
that's entirely online.

00:21:30.819 --> 00:21:33.819
But I would say like that's probably an area

00:21:33.819 --> 00:21:37.099
where we need to kind of like work on things a bit more.

00:21:37.099 --> 00:21:38.660
I think it is like the Ottawa people

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:41.219
who are most excited about the group.

00:21:41.219 --> 00:21:43.500
But the other thing that we do as well

00:21:43.500 --> 00:21:45.380
is like there's been a few times

00:21:45.380 --> 00:21:49.939
where we've sent like stickers or other merch

00:21:49.939 --> 00:21:52.579
to offices outside of Ottawa, so.

00:21:53.420 --> 00:21:54.900
Cool, thank you so much.

00:21:54.900 --> 00:21:55.739
Thank you.

00:21:55.979 --> 00:21:57.060
Thank you.

00:21:57.060 --> 00:21:58.020
Thank you.

00:21:58.020 --> 00:21:58.859
Thank you.

00:21:58.859 --> 00:22:01.660
Thank you.

